  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN160-kilavi">tōḻi varaivu malintu colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">What the confidante said when rejoicing in the marriage.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="AN160">
              <l><anchor n="1"/>oṭuṅkī rōti niṉakku maṟṟō</l>
              <l>naṭuṅkiṉ ṟaḷitte ṉiṟaiyi ṉeñca</l>
              <l>maṭumpukoṭi citaiya vāṅkik koṭuṅkaḻik</l>
              <l>kuppai veṇmaṇaṟ pakkañ cērtti</l>
              <l>niṟaiccūl yāmai maṟait<supplied>tī</supplied>ṉṟu putaitta</l>
              <l>kōṭṭuvaṭ ṭuruviṉ pulavunāṟu muṭṭaip</l>
              <l>pārppiṭa ṉāku maḷavaip pakuvāyk</l>
              <l>kaṇava ṉōmpuṅ kāṉalañ cērppaṉ</l>
              <l>muḷ<supplied>ḷu</supplied>ṟiṟ ciṟatta lañci mella</l>
              <l>vāyuṭai maiyiṉ vārpiṟ kāṭṭi</l>
              <l>vēttoḻi ṉaviṉṟa veḻiṉaṭaip puravi</l>
              <l>ceḻunīrt taṇkaḻi nīntali ṉāḻi</l>
              <l>nutimukaṅ kuṟaitta potimukiḻ neytal</l>
              <l>pāmpuyar talaiyiṟ cāmpuvaṉa nivappa</l>
              <l>viravan taṉṟāṟ ṟiṇṭēr karavā</l>
              <l>tolleṉa volikku miḷaiyaroṭu valvā</l>
              <l>yaravac cīṟūr kāṇap</l>
              <l>pakalvan taṉṟāṟ pāypari ciṟantē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l>O you with oil-soothed hair, [is] it thus for you too? (1)</l>
                <l>My overfull heart has started to shiver, pitiable. (2)</l>
                <l>The man from the coast with shore groves, where the split-mouthed husband</l>
                <l>[of the tortoise] protects, until the young ones come out, (7f.)</l>
                <l>the fish-reeking eggs in the shape of pawns [made] from a horn (6)</l>
                <l>that were secretly brought forth [and] buried by the fully pregnant [female] tortoise (5)</l>
                <l>by joining [over them two] sides of heaped white sand (4)</l>
                <l>near the winding backwaters, pulling, so that they are spoilt, at the Aṭumpu creepers, (3)</l>
                <l>[his] firm chariot [used to] come at night indeed, (15a-c)</l> 
                <l>so that they come up withering like erect snakes’ heads, (14)</l>
                <l>the blue waterlilies with buds in bundles that where shortened by the pointed rims (13)</l>
                <l>of the wheels, as the horses crossed the cool backwaters</l>
                <l>with ample water, [their] graceful gait practised with harsh effort, (11f.)</l>
                <l>upon being shown the lash, for [its] capacity to bite, (10)</l>
                <l>softly, afraid it might be too much, if they experience the thorn. (9)</l>
                <l rend="indent8">[Now], without hiding (15d.)</l>
                <l>it has really come at midday, excelling in leaping motion, (18)</l>
                <l>for the harsh-mouthed, noisy little village to see, (16d-17)</l>
                <l>along with the young men who shout loudly. (16a-c)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>

